gen_wcdata and test_wcdata tools
================================

Use gen_wcdata to generate the header files for new versions of
iswalpha.c, iswpunct.c, wcwidth.c and towctrans.c. (The 'make all'
recipe will do this automatically).

The new functions are half the binary size of the old musl functions
(as measured by binutils 'size' tool). The new encoding also features
a speed improvement, with lookups for 80-90% of code blocks done with
fewer memory loads than existing functions.

The remaining Unicode blocks are niche uses, and are accessed with
1-2 more memory loads. Compared to the old musl encoding (which used
two level table) the topmost level remains much the same, providing
offsets into code block units (256 codepoint granularity). The second
level data uses fixed sizes, of one 32 bit word per codepage (where
each 2 bit pair in word identifies a block of 16 codepoints as all 0,
all 1, or mixed). The third level is a variable length series of 'ext'
extension bytes, indexed by the popcount of set high bits within the
second level's 32 bit word. Popcount is used as not all 16 codepoint
blocks need an extension byte. This popcount is calculated with nearly
the same latency as a 32 bit multiply (so it is comparable with the
indexing speed of accessing a 2D array of non power of 2 size), but
has the advantage of greater compactness for sparse data.

The command line syntax below is accepted. The 'a', 'p', 'w' letters
generate iswalpha_table.h, iswpunct_table.h and wcwidth_table.h, and
the upper case letters generate the the _dict.h header files. The 'c'
and 'C' letters generates the corresponding files for towctrans.

    gen_wcdata [-v] a|p|w|c|A|P|W|C

Also, if compiled together with the functions source, it will do tests
of these wctype/wchar functions against this repo's Unicode data.
If compiled as just the gen_wcdata.c source file alone, the tool tests
against the compiler's C library equivalent functions.

To test against the compiler C library functions, execute the following
(where 'a' tests iswalpha, 'p' tests iswpunct, 'w' tests wcwidth and
'l'/'u' test towctrans lower & upper case):

    gen_wcdata -t|-T a|p|w|l|u

Although gen_wcdata is a full replacement for gen_ctype, gen_wide,
gen_nonspacing and gen_casemap, these tools are retained for regression
testing, and hence are moved into a 'deprecated' sub-directory.

A test recipe has been added to Makefile to generate both new and old
header files, and compile test_wcdata with new & old source files.
To run these tests, execute:

    make test

Alternatively, the test_wcdata tool can be run directly using:

    test_wcdata -t|-T a|p|w|l|u

or (to test older musl functions) using:

    test_wcdata_deprec -t|-T a|p|w|l|u


